<section xml:id="sec_second-intro" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Algebra of Vectors</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      The mathematical operations of addition, subtraction, and multiplication in 
      the algebra of numbers are also capable of getting extension in an algebra of vectors. 
      A vector whose effect is same as that of a set of two vectors is called the 
      <term>resultant</term> of the given  vectors. Let  <m>\vec{OP} = \vec{a}</m> and 
      <m>\vec{PQ} = \vec{b}</m> are two vectors as shown in <xref first="fig2i" last="fig2ii" />, 
      then the resultant vector <m>\vec{OQ} = \vec{r}</m> is the sum of 
      <m>\vec{a}</m> and <m>\vec{b}</m>, i.e., <m>\vec{r}=\vec{a} + \vec{b}</m> as shown in 
      <xref ref="fig2ai"/>.  
    </p> 

    <figure>
      <caption>Vector Algebra</caption>
      <sidebyside widths="20% 15% 30% 25%">
          <figure xml:id="fig2i">
              <caption></caption>
              <image source="fig2i.png"/>
          </figure>
          <figure xml:id="fig2ii">
              <caption></caption>
              <image source="fig2ii.png"/>
          </figure>
          <figure xml:id="fig2ai">
              <caption></caption>
              <image source="fig2ai.png"/>
          </figure>
          <figure xml:id="fig2bi">
              <caption></caption>
              <image source="fig2bi.png"/>
          </figure>
       </sidebyside>
  </figure>
<p>
  The resultant vector <m>\vec{r'}</m> or the subtraction of <m>\vec{b}</m>  from <m>\vec{a}</m>  
  is the addition of a negative vector of <m>\vec{b}</m> (i.e., <m>-\vec{b}</m>)  to a 
  <m>\vec{a}</m>, i.e., 
  <me>
    \vec{r'} = \vec{a} - \vec{b} = \vec{a} + (-\vec{b})
  </me>
   as shown in <xref ref="fig2bi"/>. 
The resultant vector can be obtained by arranging  the two individual vectors in such a way 
that  the head of one vector falls onto the tail of another one without changing their individual 
directions. The resultant vector then joins the tail of first vector to the head of second vector 
(Remember the resultant vector is not in cyclic orientation of the individual vectors). 
If a  vector <m>\vec{a}</m> is multiplied by any real positive number <m>n</m>, then the 
product <m>n \vec{a}</m> is a vector whose magnitude is <m>n</m> times as that of <m>\vec{a}</m> 
and its direction is the same as <m>\vec{a}</m>. If <m>n</m> is a negative number then the 
direction of <m>n \vec{a}</m> is opposite to <m>\vec{a}</m>. If <m>\hat{a}</m> is a unit vector 
in the direction of <m>\vec{a}</m> then, we have 
<ol marker="i.">
  <li>
    <m>\vec{a} = |a| \hat{a},</m> where <m>|a|</m> is a magnitude of <m>\vec{a}</m>.
  </li>
  <li>
    <m>(k+l)\vec{a} = (k+l)a \hat{a}  = k a \hat{a} + l a \hat{a} = k \vec{a} + l \vec{a},</m> 
    where <m>k</m> and <m>l</m> are scalars.
  </li>
  <li>
    <m>k(\vec{a} + \vec{b}) = k \vec{a} + k\vec{b}</m>.
  </li>
  <li>
    <m>k(l\vec{a}) = (k l) \vec{a}</m>.
  </li>
</ol>
</p>
  </introduction>
<subsection xml:id="subsec-compnt_vect">
  <title>Components of a Vector:</title>
  <p>
    A vector <m>\vec{r}</m> can be resolved into its components in a coordinate system. 
    Suppose a vector <m>\vec{a}</m> is lying on the xy-plane as shown in <xref ref="fig2ci"/>, 
    then its x- and y- components are given as <m>\vec{a_{x}}</m> and <m>\vec{a_{y}}</m>, 
    respectively. Hence the vector <m>\vec{a} </m> can be written as 
  </p>
  <figure>
    <caption>Vector Components</caption>
    <sidebyside widths="30% 30%">
        <figure xml:id="fig2ci">
            <caption></caption>
            <image source="fig2ci.png"/>
        </figure>
        <figure xml:id="fig2cii">
            <caption></caption>
            <image source="fig2cii.png"/>
        </figure>
     </sidebyside>
</figure>
<p>
  <me>
    \vec{a} =  \vec{a_{x}}  +  \vec{a_{y}} =  a_{x}\hat{i}  +  a_{y}\hat{j} =a\cos\theta \hat{i}+a\sin\theta \hat{j}
  </me>

where <m>a_{x} =a\cos\theta</m> and <m>a_{y}=a\sin\theta </m> are the magnitude of vector 
components <m>\vec{a_{x}}</m>  and <m>\vec{a_{y}}</m>, respectively.  The magnitude of vector 
<m>\vec{a} </m> is given by
<me>
  a^{2}= a^{2}_{x}+a^{2}_{y} \quad \Rightarrow |\vec{a}|=\sqrt{a^{2}_{x}+a^{2}_{y}}.
</me>

The direction of <m>\vec{a}</m> can be obtained by 
<me>
  \tan\theta =\frac{a_{y}}{a_{x}} \quad \Rightarrow \theta=\tan^{-1}\frac{a_{y}}{a_{x}}.
</me>

Let the diagonal vector of a parallelopiped,  <m>\vec{OP} = \vec{r}</m> is described by a 
coordinate (x,y,z) in a rectangular system as shown in <xref ref="fig2cii"/> and 
<m>\hat{i}</m>,  <m>\hat{j}</m>, and <m>\hat{k}</m> are the unit vectors along <m>OX</m>, 
<m>OY</m>, and <m>OZ</m> axes, respectively then  <m>\vec{OA} = x \hat{i}</m>, 
<m>\vec{OB} = y \hat{j}</m>, and  <m>\vec{OC} = z \hat{k}</m> are the rectangular components 
of <m>\vec{r}</m>. Now,
<men xml:id="eqn-vect_comp1">
  \vec{r} = \vec{OP} = (\vec{OF} + \vec{FP})  
</men>
<men xml:id="eqn-vect_comp2">
 \text{and} \quad \vec{OF} = \vec{OA} + \vec{AF} 
</men>
<men xml:id="eqn-vect_comp3">
  \therefore \quad \vec{r} = \vec{OA} + \vec{OB} + \vec{OC} = x \hat{i} + y \hat{j} + z \hat{k} 
</men>
<me>
  \because\quad \vec{AF}= \vec{OB}; \quad \vec{FP} = \vec{OC} 
</me>

If <m>\vec{OP}</m> makes angles <m>\alpha</m>, <m>\beta</m>, and <m>\gamma</m> with OX, OY, 
and OZ axes, respectively then <m> x=r\cos\alpha</m>, <m>y=r\cos\beta</m>, and <m>z=r\cos\gamma</m>.
</p>
</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="subsec-vect_mult">
  <title>Product of Two Vectors:</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      <idx><h>vectors Product</h></idx>There are two ways in which vectors can be multiplied. The product of one of them is 
      a scalar quantity, called a scalar product (or a dot product) and the other is a vector 
      quantity, called a vector product (or a cross product).
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-dot_product">
    <title>Scalar (or Dot) Product</title>
    <p>
      The scalar product of two vectors <m>\vec{a}</m> and <m>\vec{b}</m> is denoted by 
      <m>\vec{a}\cdot \vec{b}</m>, and is defined as 
      <me>
        \vec{a}\cdot {\vec{b}} = |\vec{a}| |\vec{b}| \cos\theta = ab\cos\theta,
      </me>
      where  <m>\theta</m> is the angle between <m>\vec{a}</m> and <m>\vec{b}</m>.
    </p>
    <paragraphs>
      <title>Geometrical Interpretation:</title>
      <p>
        Let <m>\vec{OA} =\vec{a}</m> and <m> \vec{OB} =\vec{b}</m>,  as shown in <xref ref="fig2d"/>, then 
        <me>
          \vec{a}\cdot {\vec{b}} =  \vec{OA}\cdot {\vec{OB}} = (OA)(OB) \cos\theta = (OA)(ON)  
        </me>
        =  (length of <m>\vec{a}</m>) (projection of <m>\vec{b}</m> along <m>\vec{a}</m>).
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="fig2d">
        <caption></caption>
        <image source="fig2d.png" width="30%"/>
    </figure>
    <p>
     Therefore the dot product of two vectors is the product of length of one of these vectors and 
      the projection of the other in the direction of the first. 
    </p>
    </paragraphs>
    <p>
      <alert>Mnemonics:</alert>
      <me>
        \hat{i}\cdot\hat{j}= \hat{j}\cdot\hat{k} = \hat{k}\cdot\hat{i} = 0
      </me>
      or,
      <me>
        \hat{i}\cdot\hat{i} =\hat{j}\cdot\hat{j} = \hat{k}\cdot\hat{k} =1
      </me>
    </p>
    <p>
      <alert>Properties:</alert>
      <ol>
        <li>
          Commutative law: <m>\quad \vec{a} \cdot \vec{b} = \vec{b} \cdot \vec{a}</m>
        </li>
        <li>Distributive law: <m>\quad \vec{a} \cdot \left(\vec{b}+\vec{c} \right) = \vec{a} \cdot \vec{b} + \vec{a} \cdot \vec{c}</m></li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </subsubsection>
 
  <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-cross_product">
    <title>Vector (or Cross) Product</title>
    <p>
      The vector product of two vectors <m>\vec{a}</m> and <m>\vec{b}</m> is denoted by 
      <m>\vec{a}\times\vec{b}</m> and is defined as  
      <me>
        \vec{a} \times \vec{b} = \mid{\vec{a}}\mid \mid{\vec{b}}\mid sin\theta \hat {n} = absin\theta {\hat{n}},
      </me>
where <m>\theta</m> is the angle between <m>\vec{a}</m> and <m>\vec{b}</m>, and <m>{\hat{n}}</m> 
is a unit vector perpendicular to the plane made by vectors <m>\vec{a}</m> and <m>\vec{b}</m>, 
and is representing the direction of <m>\vec{a}\times\vec{b}</m>. Here <m>\vec{a}</m>, 
<m>\vec{b}</m>, and <m>{\hat{n}}</m> form a right handed system, as shown in <xref ref="fig2di"/>.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <caption>Vector Product of Two Vectors</caption>
      <sidebyside widths="30% 30% 30%">
          <figure xml:id="fig2di">
              <caption></caption>
              <image source="fig2di.png"/>
          </figure>
          <figure xml:id="fig2dii">
              <caption></caption>
              <image source="fig2dii.png"/>
          </figure>
          <figure xml:id="fig2diii">
            <caption></caption>
            <image source="fig2diii.png"/>
        </figure>
       </sidebyside>
  </figure>

  <paragraphs>
    <title>Geometrical Interpretation:</title>
    <p>
Let <m>\vec{a}</m> and <m>\vec{b}</m> be the adjacent sides of the parallelogram, as shown in 
<xref ref="fig2dii"/>, then  
<me>
  \vec{a}\times\vec{b} = \vec{OA}\times\vec{OB} = (OA)(OB) \sin\theta \hat{n} = \left(OA\cdot{BM}\right){\hat{n}}  = base \cdot height \quad \hat{n}
</me>
 = vector area of parallelogram OACB.
    </p>
    <p>
      i.e., a vector product of two vectors is the vector area of a parallelogram constructed by these vectors.
    </p>
  </paragraphs>
  <paragraphs>
    <title>Vector product in determinant form</title>
    <p>
      If <m>\vec{a} = a_{1}\hat{i}+a_{2}\hat{j}+ a_{3}\hat{k}</m> and 
      <m>\vec{b} = b_{1}\hat{i}+b_{2}\hat{j}+ b_{3}\hat{k}</m>  then 
      <me>
        \vec{a}\times\vec{b} =\left( {a_{1}\hat{i}+a_{2}\hat{j}+ a_{3}\hat{k}}\right)\times \left( {b_{1}\hat{i}+b_{2}\hat{j}+ b_{3}\hat{k}}\right)
      </me>
      <me>
        =(a_{2}b_{3}-a_{3}b_{2})\hat{i}- (a_{1}b_{3}-a_{3}b_{1})\hat{j} + (a_{1}b_{2}-a_{2}b_{1})\hat{k}
      </me>
      <me>
        =\begin{bmatrix} \hat{i} &amp; \hat{j} &amp; \hat{k} \\a_{1} &amp; a_{2} &amp; a_{3} \\ b_{1} &amp; b_{2} &amp; b_{3} \end{bmatrix} 
      </me>
    </p>
  </paragraphs>

  <paragraphs>
    <title>Mnemonics:</title>
    <p>
      <me>
        \hat{i}\times\hat{j}=\hat{k};\qquad \hat{j}\times\hat{k}=\hat{i};\qquad \hat{k}\times\hat{i}=\hat{j}
      </me>
      or,
      <me>
        \hat{i}\times\hat{k}=-\hat{j};\qquad \hat{k}\times\hat{j}=-\hat{i};\qquad \hat{j}\times\hat{i}=-\hat{k}
      </me>
      
    </p>
  </paragraphs>

  <paragraphs>
    <title>Properties:</title>
    <p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          Commutative Law: <m>\quad \vec{a} \times \vec{b} \neq \vec{b} \times \vec{a}</m> 
        </li>
        <li>
          Distributive law: <m>\quad \vec{a} \times \left(\vec{b}+\vec{c} \right) = \vec{a} \times \vec{b} + \vec{a} \times \vec{c}</m> 
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </paragraphs>
  </subsubsection>
</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="subsec-axis_transform">
  <title>Transformation of Axis</title>
  <figure xml:id="fig2e">
    <caption></caption>
    <image source="fig2e.png" width="30%"/>
</figure>
  <p>
    <me>
      x'=OL'= OT+TL' = OT +SL = OL\cos\theta +PL\sin\theta 
    </me>
    <me>
      \therefore x'  = x\cos\theta +y\sin\theta 
    </me>
    <me>
      y'=PL'= PS-L'S =PS-TL = PL\cos\theta -OL\sin\theta 
    </me>
    <me>
      \therefore y'  = y\cos\theta -x\sin\theta
    </me>
    <me>
      \therefore \hat{i'}=\hat{i}\cos\theta +\hat{j}\sin\theta \qquad \text{also} \quad  \hat{j'}=-\hat{i}\sin\theta +\hat{j}\cos\theta
    </me>
    Now,
    <me>
      \vec{r}=\hat{i'}x'+\hat{j'}y'= [\hat{i}\cos\theta +\hat{j}\sin\theta]x'+[-\hat{i}\sin\theta +\hat{j}\cos\theta]y'
    </me>
    <me>
      \therefore \vec{r}=\hat{i}[x'\cos\theta -y'\sin\theta] +\hat{j}[x'\sin\theta +y'\cos\theta] =\hat{i}x+\hat{i}y
    </me>
  </p>
</subsection>
  </section>

